    <h1>Understanding Arrays in Programming</h1>
    <p>
      Arrays are a fundamental data structure used to store collections of
      elements. They are used in almost every programming language. An array can
      store numbers, strings, objects, or even other arrays. The elements in an
      array are indexed, which means each item has a corresponding number that
      you can use to access it. This makes arrays very useful for storing data
      that needs to be accessed in an ordered way.
    </p>

    <h2>Characteristics of Arrays:</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Indexed: Each element has a numerical index, starting from 0.</li>
      <li>Ordered: The elements in an array are stored in a specific order.</li>
      <li>
        Mutable: You can modify the elements of an array after it's created.
      </li>
      <li>
        Size-variable: Some languages have arrays that can change in size, while
        others have fixed-size arrays.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Common Operations on Arrays:</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Accessing elements using their index.</li>
      <li>Iterating over all elements with loops.</li>
      <li>Adding new elements to the array.</li>
      <li>Removing elements from the array.</li>
      <li>Finding elements within the array.</li>
      <li>Sorting the array.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example of an Array in JavaScript:</h2>
    <pre>
        <code>
            let fruits = ['Apple', 'Banana', 'Cherry'];
            console.log(fruits[0]); // Output: Apple
            fruits.push('Date');
            console.log(fruits); // Output: ['Apple', 'Banana', 'Cherry', 'Date']
        </code>
    </pre>

    <% if (arrayExample && arrayExample.length > 0) { %>
    <h2>Dynamic Array Example:</h2>
    <p>The following is an example of an array passed to this EJS template:</p>
    <ul>
      <% arrayExample.forEach(function(element) { %>
      <li><%= element %></li>
      <% }); %>
    </ul>
    <% } else { %>
    <p>No array data was passed to the template.</p>
    <% } %>
  </body>
